Note: ========================================
Note: WebAssembly (WAT) Parser
Note: ========================================
Note: S-expression parser for WAT modules
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/wasm/wasm_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Constant WASM_MODULE as Integer is 1
Constant WASM_FUNCTION as Integer is 2
Constant WASM_PARAM as Integer is 3
Constant WASM_RESULT as Integer is 4
Constant WASM_LOCAL as Integer is 5
Constant WASM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 6
Constant WASM_TYPE as Integer is 7
Constant WASM_IMPORT as Integer is 8
Constant WASM_EXPORT as Integer is 9

@Reasoning:
WAT s-expressions form arbitrarily nested trees, so every parsed construct is uniformly represented as a tagged node with a value slice and a child list. This single shape lets the parser stay recursive without per-construct AST classes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-field layout: discriminator tag (WASM_MODULE / WASM_FUNCTION / etc), pointer to the lexeme text, byte length of that lexeme, and a heap List of child node pointers.
@End Implementation

Type called "WasmNode":
    node_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    value_length as Integer
    children as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Allocate a new tree node up-front so that the recursive descent walker can attach children without revisiting the node after construction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reserve 32 bytes (four 8-byte slots), store node_type / value / value_length, then materialize an empty List for the children slot and return the raw node pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) allocation per node plus the List header. Total node count is proportional to source token count.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "create_wasm_node" takes node_type as Integer, value as Integer, value_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_length
    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, children
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser owns the AST it produces; recursive destruction prevents the children-List from leaking when callers discard a module subtree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk the child List, recursively destroy each child, dispose the List itself, then release the 32-byte node block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in the total number of descendant nodes; one allocator call per node.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "destroy_wasm_node" takes node as Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        proc destroy_wasm_node with child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc destroy from List with children
    proc deallocate from Layout with node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Building the tree from inside parse_sexpr requires a one-line helper that hides the children-slot offset and keeps the caller free of layout details.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the children List pointer from offset 24 of the parent node and push the child pointer onto it.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24
    proc push from List with children, child
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser is a cursor over the lexer's token stream; bundling lexer, token list, and current index keeps token lookahead and consumption inexpensive.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three slots: backing lexer (owns token storage), cached pointer to the token List, and the integer index of the next unconsumed token.
@End Implementation

Type called "WasmParser":
    lexer as Integer
    tokens as Integer
    current as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Hoist the token list pointer out of the lexer at parser-construction so the hot path advance_token / current_token avoids one memory_get_int64 per call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 24 bytes, store the lexer pointer, copy the token-list pointer from lexer offset 24 into parser offset 8, and initialize the cursor to index 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, tokens
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0
    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser only owns its own 24-byte struct; the lexer and token storage have separate lifetimes managed by the caller, so destruction is intentionally minimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Release the parser block only; lexer and token list are not touched.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_parser" takes parser as Integer:
    proc deallocate from Layout with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead is the single most frequent operation in recursive descent; centralizing it in one helper keeps the hot path consistent and the cursor logic in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read tokens pointer from offset 8 and cursor index from offset 16, then return the List entry at that index. Out-of-range access is the caller's responsibility.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) with two memory loads and one List index lookup.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Return proc get from List with tokens, current
End Process

@Reasoning:
Token consumption must happen exactly once per accepted token; isolating the cursor bump in one helper guarantees that invariant is not violated by ad-hoc increments.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Load cursor index from offset 16, add one, store back. No bounds check; the parser is expected to verify with check_token_type / current_token before calling.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer:
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, current plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate-style lookahead lets every production decide between alternatives without copying token-shape inspection logic into every site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Fetch the current token; if null pointer return 0. Otherwise read the type tag from offset 0 and return 1 on match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
    If type is equal to token_type:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Compare a source-buffer lexeme view (pointer + length) against a NUL-terminated
literal. parse_sexpr classifies the head keyword of every nested s-expression by
its byte content, so the comparator must match the lexeme exactly - including
length - to avoid "param" matching a "parameter"-like prefix.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reject immediately if the lexeme length differs from the literal length, then
compare byte-for-byte, short-circuiting to 0 on the first mismatch. Returns 1
only on a full-length exact match.
@End Implementation

Process called "lexeme_equals" takes text as Integer, text_length as Integer, literal as String, literal_length as Integer returns Integer:
    If text_length is not equal to literal_length:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than text_length:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with literal, i
        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT s-expressions are uniform "(head ...)" forms, but the head keyword
determines the structural role of the construct (a function, a parameter, an
export, an instruction, ...). Mapping the head lexeme onto the WasmNode tag at
parse time lets the downstream translator dispatch on node_type without
re-inspecting lexeme bytes, and - critically - lets wasm_to_hir's PARAM / RESULT
/ LOCAL / IMPORT / EXPORT / TYPE handlers actually fire instead of every
keyword-headed form collapsing into a single function tag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Match the head lexeme against the structural WAT keywords in descending
specificity. "func" -> WASM_FUNCTION, "param" -> WASM_PARAM, "result" ->
WASM_RESULT, "local" -> WASM_LOCAL, "import" -> WASM_IMPORT, "export" ->
WASM_EXPORT, "type" -> WASM_TYPE. Anything else (i32.add, local.get, call, nop,
memory, global, table, ...) is an instruction or a construct the body treats
uniformly as WASM_INSTRUCTION.
@End Implementation

Process called "classify_head" takes value_ptr as Integer, value_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_func be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "func", 4
    If is_func is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_FUNCTION
    End If
    Let is_param be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "param", 5
    If is_param is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_PARAM
    End If
    Let is_result be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "result", 6
    If is_result is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_RESULT
    End If
    Let is_local be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "local", 5
    If is_local is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_LOCAL
    End If
    Let is_import be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "import", 6
    If is_import is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_IMPORT
    End If
    Let is_export be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "export", 6
    If is_export is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_EXPORT
    End If
    Let is_type be proc lexeme_equals with value_ptr, value_length, "type", 4
    If is_type is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_TYPE
    End If
    Return WASM_INSTRUCTION
End Process

@Reasoning:
The top-level WAT production is (module ...); enforcing the leading "(module" pair at this entry point keeps subsequent recursion in parse_sexpr ignorant of file-level shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Require an LPAREN, then consume the identifier that names the module, allocate a WASM_MODULE node, and loop collecting child s-expressions until the matching RPAREN.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in the number of WAT tokens; one allocation per AST node.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes untrusted WAT source; relies on the lexer to bound token storage. A malformed input with unbalanced parens drives parse_sexpr's loop until the token stream is exhausted - callers must validate parse depth on adversarial inputs.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_lparen be proc check_token_type with parser, 1
    If is_lparen is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let module_node be proc create_wasm_node with WASM_MODULE, value_ptr, value_length
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let body_token be proc current_token with parser
        If body_token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let is_rparen be proc check_token_type with parser, 2
        If is_rparen is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Break
        End If
        Let is_open be proc check_token_type with parser, 1
        If is_open is not equal to 1:
            Note: Forward-progress guard: a stray non-paren token at module level
            Note: is not a valid section head. parse_sexpr would decline without
            Note: consuming it, pinning this loop, so skip the token explicitly.
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Let child be proc parse_sexpr with parser
            If child is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with module_node, child
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return module_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT's grammar is uniformly s-expression - every nested construct is a parenthesized head identifier followed by children - so a single recursive helper handles every depth without per-construct branches.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
After requiring "(", read the head lexeme and classify it via classify_head into
the structural WasmNode tag (WASM_FUNCTION / WASM_PARAM / WASM_RESULT /
WASM_LOCAL / WASM_IMPORT / WASM_EXPORT / WASM_TYPE / WASM_INSTRUCTION). The head
lexeme is stored on the node value so the instruction translator can recover the
opcode text. Loop collecting children: nested "(" recurses, plain tokens become
WASM_TYPE leaves carrying their own lexeme, ")" terminates. A null token inside
the body terminates the loop to keep an unbalanced input from spinning.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) tokens per call across the full recursion. Stack depth bounded by source nesting depth.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pathologically deep s-expressions can exhaust the native stack. Callers parsing untrusted WAT should reject inputs whose paren-depth exceeds a configured limit before reaching this routine. The body loop terminates on a null (exhausted) token so a missing closing paren cannot drive an unbounded loop.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_sexpr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_lparen be proc check_token_type with parser, 1
    If is_lparen is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node_type be proc classify_head with value_ptr, value_length
    Let node be proc create_wasm_node with node_type, value_ptr, value_length
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let body_token be proc current_token with parser
        If body_token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let is_rparen be proc check_token_type with parser, 2
        If is_rparen is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Break
        End If
        Set is_lparen to proc check_token_type with parser, 1
        If is_lparen is equal to 1:
            Let child be proc parse_sexpr with parser
            If child is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with node, child
            Otherwise:
                Note: parse_sexpr declines only when the current token is not an
                Note: opening paren; since we just checked it IS one, a 0 return
                Note: means the stream is exhausted. Stop to preserve progress.
                Break
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Let leaf_token be proc current_token with parser
            Let leaf_value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with leaf_token, 8
            Let leaf_value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with leaf_token, 16
            Let leaf_node be proc create_wasm_node with WASM_TYPE, leaf_value_ptr, leaf_value_length
            proc add_child with node, leaf_node
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End While
    Return node
End Process
